%U A396468 8092491,10460252,13378572,16945325,21270879,26479116,32708494,40113145,48864015,59150046
%N A396468 a(n) is the number of distinct triples of triangles chosen from n^2 unit triangles of a triangular grid up to rotation and triples in which all three triangles lie in the same row parallel to a side of the grid.
%C A396468 Oblique coordinate system is defined taking X axis and Y axis along two edges of the triangular grid of unit triangles n^2. Side length of a unit triangle is taken as 3 units to obtain integer coordinates for the centroids of all unit triangles. Each triangle in the grid is uniquely denoted by coordinates of its centroid.
%C A396468 Triangles in a triple are in a same row parallel to a side of the triangular grid if centers of the three triangles in a triple lie in one of the two lines or two in one line and the remaining in the second line described below:
%C A396468 Parallel to AB: y = k or y = k + 1, where 1 <= k < 3n-2,
%C A396468 Parallel to AC: x = h or x = h + 1, where 1 <= h < 3n-2,
%C A396468 Parallel to BC: x + y = r or x + y = r + 1, where 1 < r <= 3n-2.
%F A396468 a(n) = A396285(n) - A006324(n-1) for n > 1. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jun 08 2026
%e A396468 A396285(3) has 30 sets of distinct triples and the following 11 sets are in a same row parallel to AB or BC or CA:
%e A396468  {(1,1), (1,4), (1,7)},
%e A396468  {(1,1), (1,4), (2,2)},
%e A396468  {(1,1), (1,4), (2,5)},
%e A396468  {(1,1), (1,7), (2,2)},
%e A396468  {(1,1), (1,7), (2,5)},
%e A396468  {(1,1), (2,2), (2,5)},
%e A396468  {(1,1), (2,2), (5,2)},
%e A396468  {(1,1), (2,2), (4,1)},
%e A396468  {(1,1), (4,1), (5,2)},
%e A396468  {(1,4), (2,2), (2,5)},
%e A396468  {(1,4), (2,2), (4,1)}.
%e A396468 Therefore a(3) = 30 - 11 = 19.
%Y A396468 Cf. A396285, A396467, A006324.
